{"parentUuid":"44444444-4444-4444-a444-444444444444","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/projects/datatools","sessionId":"a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wandering-emerald-falcon","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":[{"tool_use_id":"toolu_02BcDeFgHiJkLmNoPqRstuVw","type":"tool_result","content":"import pandas as pd\nimport numpy as np\nfrom dotenv import load_dotenv\nimport os\n\nload_dotenv()\n\nDATA_PATH = os.getenv('DATA_PATH', 'data/input.csv')\n\ndef load_data(path: str) -> pd.DataFrame:\n    df = pd.read_csv(path)\n    print(f'Loaded {len(df)} rows from {path}')\n    return df\n\ndef summarize(df: pd.DataFrame) -> None:\n    print(df.describe())\n    print('\\nMissing values:')\n    print(df.isnull().sum())\n\nif __name__ == '__main__':\n    df = load_data(DATA_PATH)\n    summarize(df)\n"}]},"uuid":"55555555-5555-4555-a555-555555555555","timestamp":"2026-01-15T14:23:07.345Z","permissionMode":"default"}
{"parentUuid":"55555555-5555-4555-a555-555555555555","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/projects/datatools","sessionId":"a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wandering-emerald-falcon","type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_03Cc4Dd5Ee6Ff7Gg8Hh9Ii0J","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Your `requirements.txt` does list `pandas==2.2.0`, so the package is declared correctly. The issue is almost certainly that you're running the script outside of your virtual environment, so Python can't find the installed packages.\n\nHere's how to fix it:\n\n**1. Activate your virtual environment first:**\n```bash\n# If you're using venv\nsource .venv/bin/activate\n\n# Or if it's named 'env'\nsource env/bin/activate\n```\n\n**2. If you haven't installed the requirements into the venv yet:**\n```bash\npip install -r requirements.txt\n```\n\n**3. Then run your script:**\n```bash\npython script.py\n```\n\nYou can verify which Python / pip you're using at any point with `which python` and `which pip` — they should both point to paths inside your venv directory (e.g. `.venv/bin/python`), not a system-level path like `/usr/bin/python`.\n\nIf you don't have a venv set up yet, you can create one with:\n```bash\npython -m venv .venv\nsource .venv/bin/activate\npip install -r requirements.txt\n```"}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","usage":{"input_tokens":1450,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":228}},"requestId":"req_03CcDdEeFfGgHhIiJjKkLlMm","uuid":"66666666-6666-4666-a666-666666666666","timestamp":"2026-01-15T14:23:12.678Z"}
{"parentUuid":"66666666-6666-4666-a666-666666666666","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/projects/datatools","sessionId":"a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wandering-emerald-falcon","type":"system","subtype":"turn_duration","durationMs":9555,"timestamp":"2026-01-15T14:23:12.678Z","uuid":"77777777-7777-4777-a777-777777777777","isMeta":false}
{"parentUuid":"66666666-6666-4666-a666-666666666666","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/projects/datatools","sessionId":"a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"main","type":"user","message":{"role":"user","content":"Oh wow, that was it. I forgot I opened a new terminal tab. It works now. Is there a way to make VS Code activate the venv automatically?"},"uuid":"88888888-8888-4888-a888-888888888888","timestamp":"2026-01-15T14:24:05.901Z","permissionMode":"default"}
{"parentUuid":"88888888-8888-4888-a888-888888888888","isSidechain":false,"userType":"external","cwd":"/home/alex/projects/datatools","sessionId":"a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890","version":"2.1.69","gitBranch":"main","slug":"wandering-emerald-falcon","type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_04Dd5Ee6Ff7Gg8Hh9Ii0Jj1K","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Yes! VS Code handles this automatically if you configure it correctly.\n\n**The easiest way:** Open the Command Palette (`Ctrl+Shift+P` / `Cmd+Shift+P`), type **\"Python: Select Interpreter\"**, and choose the Python interpreter inside your `.venv` folder (it'll show something like `.venv/bin/python` with the pandas version listed).\n\nOnce selected, VS Code will:\n- Activate the venv automatically in any new **integrated terminal** you open (`Terminal > New Terminal`)\n- Use the correct interpreter for linting, IntelliSense, and running files via the play button\n\n**To make this stick for the project**, VS Code saves the choice in `.vscode/settings.json`:\n```json\n{\n  \"python.defaultInterpreterPath\": \"${workspaceFolder}/.venv/bin/python\"\n}\n```\n\nYou can also commit that file to your repo so teammates automatically get the same interpreter selection.\n\nNote: this only applies to terminals opened *inside* VS Code. If you open an external terminal you'll still need to `source .venv/bin/activate` manually."}],"stop_reason":"end_turn","usage":{"input_tokens":1680,"cache_read_input_tokens":0,"cache_creation_input_tokens":0,"output_tokens":210}},"requestId":"req_04DdEeFfGgHhIiJjKkLlMmNn","uuid":"99999999-9999-4999-a999-999999999999","timestamp":"2026-01-15T14:24:11.234Z"}
